This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it proposes a framework that employs deep Q-learning to learn policies for an agent to make selection decisions. Additionally, the paper deals with the problem of domain shift, which is a common issue in machine learning. 

The paper also deals with computer vision tasks, specifically partial domain adaptation, which involves transferring knowledge from a label-rich source domain to a label-scarce target domain. Therefore, it is also likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CV (Computer Vision). 

Furthermore, the paper involves the use of domain adversarial learning, which is a technique commonly used in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and natural language processing (cs.CL) to learn domain-invariant features. 

Finally, the paper's use of reinforcement learning to select source instances for positive transfer may also make it relevant to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.RO (Robotics), as reinforcement learning is commonly used in robotics for decision-making tasks.
